Introduce godoc command and arg variables, restructure query

* Add the -u flag (customizably) to the `go doc` command line: This
  ensures that un-exported/private names get matched & have their docs
  displayed, too.

* Add a company-go customization option for the `go doc` command line.

* Make sure that if company-go gets no package, it looks in the
  current directory. This can more reliably show documentation for the
  current package's names (including internals).

Guard against packages not present on the cache

There were some places that could have been nil, and the pcache might
just not contain an entry either. This change should guard against
these cases & use a default (no package) instead.

Integrate godoc lookup into company-go

Using the package information the 4th field in CSV output,
call `godoc` on the symbol being completed. This activates the
automatic documentation functionality for go in company.

Attach package import path to scopes, pass it through to formatters

This makes JSON and CSV formatters emit the import path for the
package defining the symbol being completed. This should help tools
like company get documentation for symbols, as gocode expects
`importpath.symbol` as input.

Rename "path" to "abspath", add a relative import path

This should let us retain each package's import path, potentially
useful for attaching to the symbols we emit (definitely useful for
gocode further down the line).

Add a feature I called "canonical aliases".

When you import a package "x", and do autocompletions which involve types from
"x", for ages gocode is adding default type alias of "x" to the types when
printing them out. This is purely for improving readability, because types
within a scope of the package are local, however they are not local to you,
usually. But there is a case when you import a package and redefine its name
via aliased import statement. E.g.

    import myio "io"

Yet, gocode didn't respect that and used default alias anyway. Sadly some
people use very ugly default aliases like "v1" (stands for version 1). To
overcome this problem a hack is added. It doesn't work in all cases, but it
works in some cases. When you import package with a custom alias for a current
file. Gocode will try to use that alias for package's own types, when you talk
to them directly via that package (e.g. accessing them directly or indirectly
via your package alias). E.g.

    package main
    import myast "go/ast"

    func main() {
        myast.NewPack#
    }

Will show myast.NewPackage function signature where types are prefix with
"myast.". However if you do something like that:

    import myio "io"
    import "compress/bzip2"
    ...
    bzip2.NewR#

bzip.NewReader function will use default "io" alias which is "io". Maybe I'll
improve the hack later to include this case as well.

Original commit message:
  cmd/compile: improve efficiency of binary export position encoding
  Use -64 instead of 0 as the magic "new file"
  line delta, since it is much less common.

  Use a new path encoding that breaks up paths
  into /-separated components, allowing
  reuse of the component strings, and making
  many re-used paths a single byte to encode.

  Bump the export version to 5.

Experimental Go 1.5 vendoring support. It's always enabled.

When package-lookup-mode is "go" (which is the default), gocode will try to
figure out a package path you're currently editing. Let's call this package
path - "X". And when importing package using path "Y", it will pretend the
package path you're importing is actually "X/vendor/Y" and only if it fails it
will look for "Y".

Seems like this is what vendoring is all about essentially.

Use "AllErrors" flag when parsing Go.

If this flag is not present, "go/parser" will stop parsing after 10 errors.
The standard library Go parser is rather good at returning partially parsed
data and the lack of this flag makes it return nothing. Which, in our case,
leads to lack of autocompletion suggestions.

This case was hard to identify as it happens only when editing rather long
functions and doesn't show up on artificial tests.

Also this patch makes error logging more detailed by using scanner.ErrorList.

Insert semicolon at the cursor location. Fixes #254.

Often when you do autocompletion, the text your cursor points at is a partial
statement. But go's parser fails to recognize that if it ends with '.' and
continues parsing assuming the statement spans multiple lines (doesn't insert
a semicolon).

This ugly hack fixes it. However, it's unclear how this hack will behave for
cases when you're in the middle of an expression.

whitespace and the cursor is on the whitespace, the code would try to
access a slice past its boundaries:

Use company-grab-word instead of a regex

The regular expression being used here doesn't always give desirable
results.

Example:

```go
thing := OtherThing()
thi // won't autocomplete to `thing`

type Foo struct {
   Bar string `bson:"foo"`
}

foo := Foo{}
foo.B // will autocomplete to `Bar`
```

Because it has a hard `.` anchor in it, it will only ever match methods
or attributes and never local variables, even though `gocode` itself
would complete both cases fine. Changing it to `company-grab-word`
satisfies both cases because we get a matching prefix.

Reimplement packages parser (package.go).

Previously, I was relying on a lot of preprocessing hacks to prepare
contents of the .[a568] files for "go/parser". But lately I promised to
reimplement that crappy portion of the gocode in IRC when I have >= 200
followers on the github. Well, here we go.

The new parser is the fork of "go/types".GcImporter. I can't use it
directly, because it has its own representation for declarations and
types. And I in turn, have my own.

New parser parses all the standard library (test.0032, imports all
packages) and performance results are quite nice. On a simple test
with cold cache gocode does autocompletion three times faster
(200ms vs 600ms). Warm cache autocompletion time stays the same
(25-30ms).

Implement new scheme for searching packages. Closes #47.

Gocode searches for packages using the following algorithm:
1. If 'lib-path' is defined, try to find package on these paths.
2. If not found and if GOPATH is defined, try to find package in
   $GOPATH/pkg/$GOOS_$GOARCH.
3. Otherwise fallback to $GOROOT/pkg/$GOOS_$GOARCH.

Add configuration facility and 'set' command.

gocode set - lists all config options
gocode set <OPTION> - lists that option
gocode set <OPTION> <VALUE> - sets that option

Config is stored in a file according to XDG base dir standard
(see: http://standards.freedesktop.org/basedir-spec/basedir-spec-latest.html)

Currently only one option is available: "propose-builtins". It is
disabled by default. If enabled proposal without context shows built-in
types, consts and functions too (like int, float, make, cmplx, etc.)
